    {
        "client_msg_id": "34056094-9fec-414a-be9f-8c06ed4e73a2",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "Awesome read! <@U019E2RJD9Q> <@U02D4UV4H52> - I’m curious about typical usage of ContentHarmony\/similar tools to build out briefs. How often do content managers just pass ContentHarmony to the writer rather than using it to write a super detailed brief?\n\nI’ve worked as a freelance writer with several SaaS companies and I find it’s more common to get a link to the tool rather than getting a detailed brief that used all the research from the tool.\n\nSo the “burden” is normally on me as the writer to make use of the data. Although that’s not necessarily a negative. Sometimes it’s hard to write a piece from a very detailed outline because I have to redo all the research to understand why all those sections were included in the first place. It’s often easier to build the outline myself as I write—as long as the client includes the key sections they really care about.",
        "user": "UUH2ESL66",
        "ts": "1648575022.002949",
        "team": "TJE58GTJL",
        "user_team": "TJE58GTJL",
        "source_team": "TJE58GTJL",
        "user_profile": {
