                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Awesome read! "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "user",
                                "user_id": "U019E2RJD9Q"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": " "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "user",
                                "user_id": "U02D4UV4H52"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": " - I’m curious about typical usage of ContentHarmony\/similar tools to build out briefs. How often do content managers just pass ContentHarmony to the writer rather than using it to write a super detailed brief?\n\nI’ve worked as a freelance writer with several SaaS companies and I find it’s more common to get a link to the tool rather than getting a detailed brief that used all the research from the tool.\n\nSo the “burden” is normally on me as the writer to make use of the data. Although that’s not necessarily a negative. Sometimes it’s hard to write a piece from a very detailed outline because I have to redo all the research to understand why all those sections were included in the first place. It’s often easier to build the outline myself as I write—as long as the client includes the key sections they really care about."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ],
        "thread_ts": "1648571726.292859",
        "parent_user_id": "UJG9WTEKG"
    },
    {
        "client_msg_id": "02559100-c09e-48c0-87f5-c4045678d410",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "I'm very biased here, but most other tools focus on giving you some data, plus a content grader, and letting you build the brief or outline manually.\n\nWe're focused on letting you build a brief from a large set of report data, then giving you a content grader as a final step in the workflow.\n\nBut depends on the type of client and type of writer and what their preferences are. Sometimes it makes sense to skip briefs, but it usually comes at the cost of more editing or disagreement between writer and client on which direction to take the content. So the brief solves a lot of those concerns upfront if it's built well.\n\nWe've actually seen writers that will charge lower rate if a full brief is provided, because it usually cuts down on research as well as edits they have to do.",
        "user": "U019E2RJD9Q",
        "ts": "1648575324.627689",
        "team": "TJE58GTJL",
        "user_team": "TJE58GTJL",
        "source_team": "TJE58GTJL",
